explanation: Screen is rigid and does not move; user must self-simulate the 4 cm travel so no true resistance or rebound is provided by the object itself.
Tilts and flexes a few millimetres with mild springiness, but motion is angular rather than straight vertical and total travel is far below 4 cm.
Foam ear-cup compresses several centimetres with progressive resistance and quick rebound, matching the stroke well; lacks a distinct bottom-out click.
Fan head can be pushed downward at its hinge and springs back, but travel is mostly tilt not pure vertical and mechanical stop/click is indistinct.
Arm press delivers increasing resistance and a crisp snap at the end, giving a nice detent, yet total travel is short (~1 cm) and surface is narrow.
Inverted cup walls buckle 1–2 cm with elastic rebound, offering some spring feel, but stroke is shorter than required and no mechanical click occurs.
Analogue stick depresses with tactile feedback, but travel is only millimetres; user must move wrist to fake the 4 cm stroke, so haptic fidelity is limited.
Compresses 3–5 cm with soft, progressive resistance and returns to shape; good stroke length but lacks defined bottom-out detent.
Bottle itself does not travel—only an impact against the tabletop occurs. No sustained resistance or rebound supplied by the object.

physicalObject: clear plastic soap dispenser with pump
explanation: Pump plunges several centimetres with smooth spring resistance, bottoms out with a soft stop, and snaps back quickly—quite close to the expected feel, just slightly shorter than 4 cm.
Foam compresses 4–6 cm and rebounds, matching stroke length and progressive resistance; however, rebound is slower and no crisp detent is present.
Shutter button offers two-stage resistance with a click, but overall travel is only a few millimetres—well short of the needed 4 cm piston motion.
Stuffing compresses deeply with smooth resistance and rebounds rapidly, giving a convincing large-button press except for the absence of a mechanical click.
Key switch provides tactile click, but displacement is about 4 mm, not 4 cm; haptic amplitude is therefore far too small.
Trigger/plunger moves with spring resistance and a soft stop, but stroke length is around 1–2 cm and alignment is angled, so only partial match.
Bean bag compresses several centimetres and rebounds slowly, fulfilling stroke length but response is mushy and lacks distinct bottom-out feedback.
The TV offers only a flat vertical pane with no raised circular cap or crisp edge definition, so the outline of a button is largely absent.

physicalObject: dual-disc metal lamp head on a stand
explanation: The upper disc is a broad, round surface raised above a lower disc, giving a recognizable circular cap with a clear edge, though the central hole and oversized diameter make it feel less exact.
The ear-cup is round and clearly elevated, but its plush rim and soft edges soften the crisp boundary expected from a hard emergency button.
Pressing the grille presents a circular area, yet the grill spokes and the gap to the outer ring blur the clean, solid outline of a button cap.
The binder clip is narrow, V-shaped, and lacks any round, raised disc; its outline is fundamentally different from a button.
The flat circular base of the inverted cup is raised several centimetres above the table by the rim, giving a distinct round cap with a clear edge very similar to a large push-button’s profile.
The stick top is a small, raised circular disc with crisp edges that read as a miniature button, though its diameter is far smaller than the expected big red button.
The top is flat and rectangular; there is no round, elevated cap or surrounding base ring, so the outline similarity is low.
The metal lid provides a small circular surface, but the cylindrical bottle body beneath lacks the distinct cap-above-base geometry of the virtual button.
The pump head is clearly raised and roughly circular/oval, giving a recognizable button cap, yet its small size and irregular shape reduce fidelity.
The cushion is a broad rectangular pad with no raised circular profile; its outline does not resemble a button at all.
A small, domed, round button with crisp edges is present, capturing the basic outline, but the diminutive diameter weakens the match.
The plush presents a large, circular, raised dome reminiscent of a giant button, though its edges are soft rather than sharply defined.
The keycap is raised with crisp edges but it is square, not round, and much smaller than the expected emergency button.

physicalObject: green cleaning spray bottle trigger nozzle
explanation: The trigger is an elongated lever rather than a round cap, so only minimal outline similarity exists.
While the bean bag offers a large domed surface, it lacks a defined edge and circular precision; its amorphous outline only loosely evokes a button.
The glass surface allows smooth gliding but is completely rigid, so the essential compliant bending of leaves is missing.

physicalObject: dual-disc metal lamp head on stand
explanation: Thin metal disc flexes a little and perforations add subtle texture, yet the stiffness and single-piece geometry limit natural, low-force leaf deflection.
Soft foam cushions compress under <0.5 N and rebound smoothly, giving compliant, vein-like edges that moderately match leaf interaction.
Individual grille spokes bend slightly and spring back, letting fingers slip through multiple flexible elements—reasonably close to brushing through foliage.
Wire arms do bend but require noticeably higher force and snap aggressively, so the gentle, compliant feel of leaves is only partially present.
Cup walls give a bit under pressure, yet the deformation is limited and lacks the many small, separate flexible surfaces characteristic of plant leaves.
Analog sticks and buttons supply low-force spring return, simulating discrete leaf bends, but the interaction points are few and strongly localized.
The loose tissue is ultra-soft, flutters with minimal contact, and readily bends and returns—closely emulating the gentle flex and texture of foliage.
Completely rigid; no compliant bending or spring-back, therefore fails to reproduce plant-leaf interactivity.
Pressing the pump provides a single springy element, but the rest of the bottle is hard; overall compliance and distributed leaf-like response are limited.
Fabric surface compresses broadly and offers mild drag, giving some soft resistance, yet lacks the many individual, flexible strands typical of leaves.
Loose woven strap moves and yields easily under the hand, resembling thin, drooping leaves slipping between fingers.
Plush filling provides soft, low-force compression and rebound, while stitched seams add vein-like texture, closely mirroring leafy compliance.
Keys spring back individually, but activation force and sharp tactile click feel unnatural compared to gentle, continuous leaf flex.
Trigger offers a single compliant motion but with noticeable mechanical resistance; overall experience lacks the broad, multiple flexible points of foliage.
Surface and inner pellets shift softly under the hand, giving a compliant feel, yet the large mass moves as one rather than as many slender leaves.
The glass panel is perfectly smooth and entirely rigid, lacking both the faint surface grain and the compliant flex or raised veins found on real leaves.

Tiny perforations give some micro-texture and the thin sheet metal bends a little, but the cool, hard metal and circular hole pattern do not resemble the subtle ridged veins and soft cuticle of foliage.

The foam cushions are softly compliant and rebound gently, while stitched seams offer low, linear ridges that hint at vein patterns; however, the surface finish feels too plush and uniform compared with slightly coarse plant skin.

Thin spokes flex back under light force, giving leaf-like spring, yet the hard plastic ribs are narrow and widely spaced, so fingertip contact misses the continuous, faintly rough lamina between veins.
Only the wire arms move; they are slender and slick, providing no broad surface or subtle micro-texture typical of a leaf blade.
The thin wall flexes slightly and returns, but its glossy, featureless smoothness lacks the mild grain and raised vein detail expected from plant tissue.
Analog sticks and buttons deliver localized compliant motion, yet the hard plastic caps and abrupt edges do not reproduce a continuous, faintly ridged leaf surface.

The tissue’s soft, slightly fibrous sheet drapes and flutters with minimal force, mirroring leaf compliance and offering a subtle paper-grain similar to fine epidermal roughness, though it is thinner and flimsier than most leaves.
A hard, polished cylinder provides no give or fine textural variation, diverging sharply from the compliant, vein-marked feel of foliage.
Depressing the pump offers some springiness, but the main contact surfaces are smooth, curved plastic with negligible surface relief, so vein cues are missing.
The cloth is mildly coarse and compresses over padding, supplying broad compliance, yet its woven pattern feels artificial and lacks the localized raised ridges of leaf veins.
The woven strap is flexible, slightly rough, and moves with the hand, evoking thin dangling leaves; still, its linear, cord-like form doesn’t give the wide, vein-patterned lamina sensation.

Velvety fabric over soft fill yields readily under <0.5 N and rebounds, while stitched panel seams create gentle raised lines reminiscent of veins, making overall tactile feedback quite leaf-like despite extra plushness.
Keys depress and spring back in a compliant manner, but each contact point is small, hard, and smooth; continuous slightly coarse texture and vein ridges are absent.
Squeezing the trigger gives light spring action paralleling stem flex, but the surrounding plastic surfaces are slick and rigid, failing to convey leaf skin grain or vein relief.

The fabric is slightly textured and the filling shifts softly underhand, delivering broad compliance; however, the coarse weave and large surface area do not match the finer raised vein details of individual leaves.
Provides only a linear slide with no axial rotation; cannot replicate the globe’s 360° spin or the feeling of inertia around a fixed vertical pivot.
Disc can be grasped on the rim and spun freely around its bolt, giving continuous rotation and mild bearing resistance similar to a small globe, though the surface is flat rather than spherical.
Ear-cups swivel and can be flicked, but range is limited and friction higher than a globe; still offers a recognizable rotational gesture when one hand stabilises the head-band.

With power off, the blades spin smoothly on a central axle, delivering low-friction inertia and gradual coast-down very close to the feel of spinning a globe, though the user pushes blades not a continuous sphere.
Wire arm rotates only ~180° and stops abruptly; lacks full circular motion and mass, so the globe-like spinning experience is only partially present.

When inverted and spun, the cup gives continuous low-friction rotation and gradual slowdown, matching the inertial feel of a globe, though the axis is through a point on the rim rather than a fixed spindle.
Thumb-stick only tilts within a small cone instead of rotating 360° freely, so it does not reproduce the sweeping tangential push or ongoing spin of a globe.
Sliding the box gives inertial motion but no axial rotation; lacks the defining rotational degrees of freedom of a globe.

Rolled sideways, the cylindrical bottle offers smooth, low-friction rotation under the palm and gradual deceleration, effectively emulating the momentum of spinning a globe though on a horizontal axis.
Twisting the bottle against a stationary pump gives controlled rotation around a vertical axis, but friction is higher and surface grip is segmented, giving a somewhat less convincing globe feel.
Only provides a curved sliding path; no true rotation or spin, so it captures gesture training but not the haptic sensation of a globe turning.
Lens rings rotate smoothly with low resistance and inertia, giving fine rotational feedback similar to fingertip spinning of a globe, albeit on a much smaller radius.
Rounded underside can roll, providing some inertial spin, but soft fabric increases friction and dampens the smooth, controlled glide expected from a hard globe.
Swiping across keys produces only intermittent bumps with no rotation or sustained movement; completely fails to replicate globe-style spinning.
Twisting the bottle offers full rotation about the vertical axis, but the screw threads and moderate friction reduce the smooth, low-inertia glide characteristic of a globe.
Rolling or pivoting the bean bag provides substantial mass and inertia similar to a large globe, but irregular shape and fabric drag make the spin less smooth and harder to start.
The glass/plastic screen is completely rigid with no elastic give; kicking it would feel nothing like the resilient compression of a soccer ball.

physicalObject: dual-disc metal lamp head on a stand
explanation: Metal surface is fully rigid and unforgiving, providing no brief compression or pop on impact.
Soft foam cushions collapse too easily while the plastic shell is small and rigid; overall compliance is far from an inflated ball’s elastic firmness.
Hard plastic grill offers no compressive give and would feel brittle rather than springy.
Tiny, rigid steel clip bears no resemblance to the compliant, air-backed firmness of a soccer ball.
Thin cup walls can flex slightly but tend to crease or crack instead of delivering a resilient compression–rebound sensation.
Rigid ABS shell with virtually zero deformation; impact would feel solid, not springy.
Cardboard box full of tissues is soft and collapses rather than briefly compressing then rebounding.
Double-walled steel body is completely rigid; no give or elastic restitution on impact.

physicalObject: clear plastic soap dispenser with pump
explanation: Slight squeezing is possible, but the body deforms slowly and lacks the quick rebound and firmness characteristic of an inflated ball.
Foam seat is too soft and thick; compression is deep and slow, offering no sharp pop back.
Rigid metal/plastic body is entirely non-compliant—opposite of the desired resilient hardness.
Extremely soft plush compresses easily and does not spring back with force; lacks required firmness.
Rigid PCB/metal plate; keys only move millimeters and do not provide any overall object compliance.
Thin plastic bottle gives slightly when squeezed but deforms slowly and lacks quick elastic restitution.
Bean bag is highly compliant and amorphous; it absorbs impact rather than rebounding sharply like a pressurized ball.
Edge provides no downward travel or spring return—only tapping on a rigid bar. No actuation point, chords, or glissando depression, so interactivity is largely missing.

physicalObject: dual-disc metal lamp head on a stand
explanation: Hinge gives slight compliant movement and rebound, but it is one large surface, not discrete keys. Travel is short and mushy; chords and glissando impossible.
Foam cups compress and rebound but lack crisp actuation or fixed travel distance. Only two ‘keys’ exist, limiting rapid isolated presses and realistic chord layout.
Grille ribs flex minimally with no distinct snap. Layout is radial, travel shallow, and rebound weak, providing limited resemblance to piano key action.
Clip arms give a firm resistance and sharp snap-back similar to a key’s actuation, but only one ‘key’ is present so chords and glissandos cannot be practiced.
Base flexes just a few millimetres and slowly rebounds; no clear actuation, little tactile definition, and only a single press point.

Multiple buttons each have defined travel, tactile actuation, and fast spring return, allowing isolated presses and small-scale chords. Travel distance is shorter than piano keys and surface area is limited for glissando, but overall resemblance is moderate.
Thin film depresses and pops back softly, giving some travel and gliding surface, but actuation is vague and there are no discrete key locations.
Cap press provides single springy action with clear bottom-out, yet only one key exists and travel distance is often shorter than required; cannot support chords or glissando.
Pump offers 1–2 cm smooth travel with definite bottom and quick spring return, closely matching one key’s feel. However, only one actuator limits chord and scale play.
Foam compresses widely and allows multi-finger presses along its length, but rebound is slow and there is no distinct 1 cm travel or actuation point, so feedback is vague.
Half-press and full-press stages create a clear actuation point, travel ≈1 cm, and strong spring return; nonetheless, it represents only a single key and cannot handle chords or fast glissando.
Very soft, deep compression with slow rebound; no distinct actuation or discrete key positions, so interaction fidelity is poor.

Offers a full array of independent switches with smooth travel, crisp actuation, rapid return, and supports chords and rapid sequences. Travel is ~4 mm (shorter than piano), but haptic pattern is otherwise highly compatible.
Trigger provides around 1 cm travel and strong spring return, giving a piano-like press for a single key. Lack of multiple keys and sideways orientation reduce fidelity.
Surface compresses deeply and sluggishly with no clear actuation or spring, so it fails to provide the precise, quick key feel needed for authentic interactivity.
The bezel supplies one long horizontal reference line that supports glissando motion, but it lacks any discrete key boundaries, so the organized array of individual keys is absent.

physicalObject: dual-disc metal lamp head on stand
explanation: Only two circular plates are available and they are stacked, not arranged in a linear row. The basic outline of a multi-key array is therefore missing.
The two ear cups give just a pair of oversized ‘keys’; this is better than a single button but still far from the orderly row of many keys expected on a keyboard.
Numerous ribs create repeated contact points, yet they are arranged radially rather than in a straight line, so spatial mapping to a piano-like keybed is weak.
Only a single squeezing element is present; there is no linear array or multiple discrete positions, so the outline of a keyboard is not represented at all.
The cup provides just one broad flexible surface with no segmentation, so users cannot perceive any organized key layout.
Multiple buttons give clear discrete contact points, but they are clustered in a small area, not lined up in a long horizontal row, limiting the sense of an extended key array.
The flexible film offers one continuous deformable zone without individual key boundaries, so the linear key outline is mostly missing.
A single pressable point cannot convey the organized arrangement of many keys.
Like the bottle, it provides only one key-like element, offering no spatial key array.
The long cushioned edge forms a horizontal strip useful for glissandos, yet it lacks any segmentation into individual keys, so spatial reference points are vague.
Only one shutter button is available, failing to suggest an organized multi-key outline.
The pillow offers a large compliant surface but no discrete, evenly spaced key shapes, so the perceived key layout is minimal.
This object already has a full linear array of discrete keys with correct size and spacing, perfectly matching the expected outline of a keyboard.
The single trigger provides one press action only, so it cannot represent the organized set of many piano keys.
While broad and compressible, the bean bag has no discrete key separations or linear guidance, giving little sense of a structured keybed.
